               "id": "introduction",
               "text": [
                  "<p><h3>Everything together</h3>Our lifespan, typically capped at just over 100 years (<htcite0>), often presents challenges in conceptualizing vast spans of time. Moreover, the inability to perceive the unseen adds another layer of complexity, underscoring the importance of approaching this material with patience and care.</p><p>As inhabitants of this planet, our gaze upwards on a nightly basis reveals but a glimpse of the stars. Over millennia, these observations have shaped our understanding of the cosmos, with outdated notions like Ptolemaic geocentrism falling by the wayside as our knowledge advances (<htcite1>). Let's delve into some key discoveries: <ul><li>The transition from geocentrism to heliocentrism prompts questions: Could the works of the Maragha observatory have influenced Nicolau Copérnico's heliocentric model? While debated, consensus remains elusive (<htcite2> ; <htcite3>). We do not have doubt that Nicolau Copérnico's showed that our planet is not the center of the universe, but rather orbits the Sun (<htcite4>).</li><li>Sir Isaac Newton's elucidation of planetary motion in subsequent centuries (<htcite5>).</li><li>It was necessary centuries for Albert Einstein to expand our understanding about gravitation (<htcite6>).</li><li>Edwin Hubble's revelation of an expanding universe (<htcite7> ; <htcite8>).</li></ul></p><p>Let's engage in a physical exercise to deepen our understanding of Hubble's work:</p>",
                  "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Expanding like the universe</b><br />Start by crossing your arms, reducing the space you occupy. Then, slowly begin to open them until they are fully extended.<br />Hubble observed a phenomenon similar to this in the universe.</div></div></p>",
                  "<p>The discovery of the universe's expansion (<htcite9>) led to a profound realization: in the distant past, all observable matter was condensed into a single point, referred to as the singularity. Simplified, a singularity is a region in space where an immense amount of matter is compressed into an extremely small volume. This was followed by a monumental expansion event known as the \"Big Bang\" (<htcite10>).</p><p>As the universe emerged from the <b>singularity</b>, it entered the Planck epoch, the initial phase of its existence. Subsequently, the first discernible entities, known as forces, began to appear (<htcite11>).</p><p>At this juncture in our study, we are providing a broad overview and introducing the works of various scientists. For a deeper understanding of the Big Bang theory, we recommend watching presentations by Sabine Hossenfelder (<htcite12>), Dr. Rebecca  Smethurst (<htcite13>), Space Today (<htcite14>) and Quantum Fracture (<htcite15>).</p>"
               ],
