               "id": "nucleosynthesis",
               "text": "<p><h3>From the smallest to the biggest</h3>The early stages of the universe were marked by considerable turbulence, hindering the formation of the smallest structures we now recognize (<htcite0>). It took three minutes after the universe emerged from the singularity for the first nuclei to appear, while the formation of the first atoms took thousands of years (<htcite1>). Our understanding of these entities is relatively recent: <ul><li>Democritus was the first to conceptualize the atom as a minuscule entity (<htcite2> ; <htcite3>).</li><li>John Dalton's groundbreaking scientific work laid the foundation for our understanding of atoms (<htcite4> ; <htcite5>)</li><li>J. J. Thomson's experimentation on Dalton's model revealed the existence of subatomic particles, such as the electron (<htcite6> ; <htcite7>).</li><li>Ernest Rutherford's experiments proposed a model reminiscent of the solar system, with a central nucleus and orbiting electrons (<htcite8> ; <htcite9>).</li><li>Niels Bohr introduced a model featuring atomic orbitals (<htcite10> ; <htcite11>)</li><li>Erwin Schrödinger proposed a equation that delivers the probability to find an atomic particle in a region (<htcite12> ; <htcite13>).</li></ul></p><p><table><tr><th>Philosophical atom</th><th>Niels Bohr atom</th><th>Quantum atom</th></tr><tr><td><img src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Atom_Philosophical.png\" /></td><td><img src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Atom_Bohr.png\" /></td><td><img src=\"images/HistoryTracers/Atom_Quantum.png\" /></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align: center; font-size: 70%;\"><b>Figure 1</b>: Simplified representation of Hydrogen Atom with different models. The source code is available in GitHub of the project (<htcite14>)</td></tr></table></p><p>Notice how we start with the concept of something small and immutable: the atom (<htcite15>). Over time, scientific inquiry refined this notion, cementing the atom's status as a fundamental building block (<htcite16> ; <htcite17>). Decades later, we uncovered an even smaller realm within the atom (<htcite18> ; <htcite19>), leading to the identification of subatomic particles (<htcite20>). Our understanding of the smallest unit has evolved, yet the fundamental principle remains: matter progresses from the minute to the massive (<htcite21>).</p><p>Similarly, our perception of the atom's structure has undergone a transformation. Referencing <b>Figure 1</b>, we initially conceived of the atom as indivisible, progressing to models featuring orbitals reminiscent of the solar system. Ultimately, we arrived at a nuanced understanding allowing for the approximate localization of electrons. Further elucidation awaits in forthcoming texts.</p>",
