               "id": "star",
               "text": "<p><h3>Star formation</h3>The process of star formation did not commence immediately in the universe; it took millions of years for the first stars to appear (<htcite0>). This delay was due to the insufficient matter available to form massive dust clouds. However, when these clouds collapse, they give rise to dense and hot nuclei capable of fusing hydrogen (H) atoms into helium atoms (He) — the very fuel of stars (<htcite1>). It's important to note that not all the mass within dust clouds undergoes this transformation; some remains as planetary material, comets, or persists as dust (<htcite2>). For a deeper understanding, we recommend watching PBS and Space Today videos (<htcite3> ; <htcite4>).</p><p>Throughout a star's lifespan, small atoms undergo fusion processes, transforming into larger atoms. However, not all known atoms are synthesized within stars. The formation of atoms is closely tied to the size of the star. The largest element produced within stars is iron (<htcite5>), while other elements are formed during cataclysmic events known as supernovae (<htcite6>).</p><p>The formation of stars ultimately gives rise to larger groupings known as galaxies (<htcite7>).<p>",
